        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Deriving Shtar from the Verse Lo Tetzei K'Tzeit Ha'Avadim",
      "display_title": "Lo Tetzei Derivation",
      "timestamp": "07:13",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The meaning of Lo Tetzei K'Tzeit Ha'Avadim and its application to Jewish slaves",
          "display_title": "Lo Tetzei Meaning",
          "timestamp": "07:13"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Drasha: she does not go out like Canaanite slaves but is acquired like Canaanite slaves",
          "display_title": "Drasha Logic",
          "timestamp": "09:41"
        },
        {
          "title": "The three acquisition methods for property (Kesef, Shtar, Chazakah) and their application to different types of slaves",
          "display_title": "Three Kinyan Methods",
          "timestamp": "10:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "The distinction: Eved Ivri has Kesef and Shtar but NOT Chazakah, demonstrating non-property status",
          "display_title": "No Chazakah Principle",
          "timestamp": "13:13"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rashi's explanation that Chazakah implies full property ownership, which does not apply to Eved Ivri",
          "display_title": "Rashi on Chazakah",
          "timestamp": "14:39"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Conceptual Question of Ownership: Contract vs Property in Eved Ivri",
      "display_title": "Ownership Concept",
      "timestamp": "15:34",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Michael's question: if Amah Ivriyah can be married with Kesef Kiddushin, why does she need Shtar?",
          "display_title": "Michael's Question",
          "timestamp": "15:34"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Dispute Over Whether Chazakah or Shtar Applies to Eved Ivri",
      "display_title": "Chazakah vs Shtar",
      "timestamp": "20:16",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The Gemara's reasoning: Shtar is preferable because it works in contexts of personal status (like Kiddushin), not just property",
          "display_title": "Shtar Preference",
          "timestamp": "20:16"
        },
        {
          "title": "Alternative argument: Chazakah is more powerful because it works even when there is no seller (Hefker property)",
          "display_title": "Chazakah Power",
          "timestamp": "20:41"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Gemara's response: Shtar works in contexts of Ishut (marriage), showing it applies to persons, not property alone",
          "display_title": "Shtar Works Persons",
          "timestamp": "21:18"
        },
        {
          "title": "The combined approach: Im Acheres Yikach Lo points to Shtar, and Lo Tetzei confirms it by exclusion of Chazakah",
          "display_title": "Combined Approach",
          "timestamp": "22:28"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Conceptual Question of Ownership: Contract vs Property in Eved Ivri (continued)",
      "display_title": "Ownership Concept…",
      "timestamp": "32:22",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The Braita teaching that Eved Ivri can acquire himself with Kesef, Shaveh Kesef, AND Shtar",
          "display_title": "Braita Sources",
          "timestamp": "32:22"
        },
        {
          "title": "The anomaly: a Shtar Admei (IOU) working as Kesef for self-redemption, challenging normal Halacha",
          "display_title": "Shtar Admei IOU",
          "timestamp": "33:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's principle: Eved Ivri's body is owned (Gufo Kanui), so Mechilas (waiving rights) alone does not free him",
          "display_title": "Rava's Principle",
          "timestamp": "36:44"
        },
        {
          "title": "The distinction between waiving contractual rights versus renouncing ownership; Tosafot's clarification on Mafkir",
          "display_title": "Waiving vs Renouncing",
          "timestamp": "38:52"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Ways an Amah Ivriyah Gains Freedom: The Mishnah's List and Reish Lakish's Addition",
      "display_title": "Amah Freedom Sources",
      "timestamp": "42:07",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The Mishnah: Amah Ivriyah is greater (Yeseira) because she goes free by Simanin (physical signs of adulthood)",
          "display_title": "Mishnah Teaching",
          "timestamp": "42:07"
        },
        {
          "title": "Reish Lakish's addition: death of the father frees her from the master by Kal V'Chomer",
          "display_title": "Reish Lakish",
          "timestamp": "42:25"
        },
        {
          "title": "The ironic comparison: Simanin do not remove her from father's control, yet they do from master's control",
          "display_title": "Ironic Comparison",
          "timestamp": "42:38"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Defending Reish Lakish: Why Death of Father is Not Listed",
      "display_title": "Defense Reish Lakish",
      "timestamp": "43:37",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Hoshaya's challenge: if death of father frees her, why doesn't the Mishnah mention it alongside Simanin?",
          "display_title": "Hoshaya Challenge",
          "timestamp": "43:37"
        },
        {
          "title": "First answer: the Mishnah is an abbreviated list, leaving off unfixed events like death of father",
          "display_title": "Abbreviated List",
          "timestamp": "44:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "The criteria: things with fixed/predictable times are taught; unfixed times are omitted",
          "display_title": "Fixed vs Unfixed",
          "timestamp": "47:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Safra's refinement: Simanin have no upper limit but have a lower limit (cannot occur before age 12)",
          "display_title": "Safra Refinement",
          "timestamp": "48:00"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Four Scenarios of Hanakah (Gifts upon Freedom): Defending Against Rav Sheshet's Challenge",
      "display_title": "Four Hanakah Scenarios",
      "timestamp": "50:10",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Shimon: four scenarios for Hanakah; three apply to men, three to women, with only Simanin exclusive to women",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Shimon",
          "timestamp": "50:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Sheshet's challenge: if death of father frees Amah Ivriyah, why not list it alongside the four enumerated scenarios?",
          "display_title": "Sheshet Challenge",
          "timestamp": "50:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "The enumeration excludes Mitat Ha'adon (death of master) and Mitat Ha'av (death of father) because both lack fixed/predictable timing",
          "display_title": "Exclusion Rationale",
          "timestamp": "52:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "The four scenarios clarified: Shanim (six years), Yovel, Yovel of Nirtza (pierced ear), and Simanin",
          "display_title": "Four Scenarios",
          "timestamp": "53:05"
        },
        {
          "title": "Conclusion: Reish Lakish's position is defended; there is a principled reason for the Mishnah's omission",
          "display_title": "Reish Lakish Defended",
          "timestamp": "55:07"
        }
      ]
    }
